Difference Between JPA, Hibernate and Spring Data JPA
1. JPA (Java Persistence API)
2. JPA is a Specification (JSR 338) for persisting and managing Java objects in a database.
3. It does not provide any implementation.
4. It defines standard annotations such as @Entity, @Table, @Id, @Column.
5. Hibernate is one of the most popular implementations of JPA.
B -->Hibernate
1. Hibernate is an ORM (Object Relational Mapping) Framework.
2. It is an implementation of JPA.
3. It maps Java objects to database tables.
4. It requires Session and Transaction management for database operations.

Hibernate Example

{ Session session = factory.openSession();
Transaction tx = session.beginTransaction();
session.save(employee);
tx.commit();
session.close(); }
C --> Spring Data JPA
1. Spring Data JPA is a Spring module built on top of JPA.
2. It does not implement JPA.
3. It reduces boilerplate code by providing JpaRepository.
4. It automatically manages transactions using @Transactional.
CRUD operations can be performed using built-in repository methods.

Spring Data JPA Example

@Autowired
private EmployeeRepository employeeRepository;

@Transactional
public void addEmployee(Employee employee) {
    employeeRepository.save(employee);
}